</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ushousetsu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shousetsu</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/psicon.gif width=13 height=13 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/17/01 7:07:49 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.newelysium.com/forum/photo.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wacom Graphire tablets?</span><hr size=1> so would I, but I was trying to make a point. <p><a href="http://www.newelysium.com"><img src="http://www.newelysium.com/banners/newelysium4.gif" border=0></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=pocus>pocus</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://homex.coolconnect.com/member3/pocus/littleicon2.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(6/17/01 8:27:54 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://homex.coolconnect.com/member3/pocus/face1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wacom Graphire tablets?</span><hr size=1> If you think you are drawing on a baseball card then maybe you should picture this. Tablet is basically like the mouse. <br>
<br>
Now you move your mouse pointer to along the side of the monitor screen. As you move, you see how much surface area your mouse use on the table/mousepad. I can tell, it's roughly less then 4x5.<br>
<br>
Another thing is, people tend to picture the tablet size as if they are going to draw that size on the screen. What I mean is when you draw on the tablet, you are looking at the monitor..not the tablet itself. So the feel ing is different from drawing on a piece of paper. Photoshop lets you zoom so much that you can add very small detail even on a 4x5. If you want gigantic pics, just zoom out all the way and stroke across with your pen...pretty much like the mouse.<br>
<br>
The only difference between a mouse and a tablet is that it's better to control using the pen and the pen is pressure sensitive. It's still technically a mouse. You can even control the desktop with it or play games with it.<br>
<br>
